[**JEP 354: Switch Expressions (Preview)**](https://openjdk.java.net/jeps/354) in JDK-13 and [**JEP 361: Switch Expressions (Standard)**](https://openjdk.java.net/jeps/361) in JDK-14 will extend the _**switch statement**_ so it can be used as an _**expression**_. 

Now you can:

 - directly assign variable from _switch expression_, 
 - use new form of switch label (`case L -&gt;`):
   &gt; The code to the right of a &quot;case L -&gt;&quot; switch label is restricted to be an expression, a block, or (for convenience) a throw statement.
 - use multiple constants per case, separated by commas, 
 - and also there are no more value _breaks_:
   &gt; To yield a value from a switch expression, the `break` with value statement is dropped in favor of a `yield` statement.

So the demo from the answers ([1](https://stackoverflow.com/a/7445174/7109598), [2](https://stackoverflow.com/a/29531341/7109598)) might look like this:

